---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Flooring Cost Estimator & Material Comparison",
  "description": "Compare costs, durability, and maintenance of different flooring types. Calculate estimated installation costs based on your room size.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "I Just Want To"
  },
  "mainEntity": {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the cheapest flooring option?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Sheet vinyl and basic laminate are typically the cheapest flooring options, often costing between $1 and $3 per square foot for materials. They are also highly DIY-friendly, which eliminates labor costs."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does new flooring increase home value?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Solid hardwood floors offer the best return on investment and are highly sought after by buyers. However, high-quality Luxury Vinyl Plank (LVP) is increasingly accepted in mid-range homes due to its durability and water resistance."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best flooring for dogs?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Luxury Vinyl Plank (LVP) and tile are generally considered the best options for pet owners. They are 100% waterproof (for accidents), highly scratch-resistant (for claws), and easy to clean. Solid hardwood is beautiful but easily scratched by large dogs."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
};
---

<SiteLayout site="ijustwantto" title="Flooring Cost Estimator & Comparison" description="Calculate the total cost of your new floors. Compare hardwood, laminate, vinyl, tile, and carpet side-by-side to find the right fit for your budget." canonical="https://ijustwantto.live/flooring-cost-estimator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Flooring Cost Estimator</h1>
      <p>Enter your square footage to instantly compare the estimated costs of five major flooring types, including standard installation labor.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tool-container card" style="text-align:center;">
      <div class="form-group" style="max-width: 400px; margin: 0 auto 2rem;">
        <label for="sqft-input" style="font-size:1.2rem; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Enter Room Square Footage:</label>
        <div style="display:flex; align-items:center; justify-content:center; gap:0.5rem;">
          <input type="number" id="sqft-input" min="10" value="500" step="10" style="width:150px; font-size:1.5rem; text-align:center; padding:0.5rem; border-radius:6px; border:2px solid var(--accent-color); background:var(--bg-color); color:var(--text-primary);">
          <span style="font-size:1.2rem; font-weight:bold; color:var(--text-secondary);">Sq Ft</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p style="font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom:1.5rem;"><em>*Costs include national average pricing for mid-grade materials and professional installation labor. Subfloor prep and demolition of old floors are not included.</em></p>

      <div class="flooring-grid" id="flooring-results">
        <!-- Cards generated by JS -->
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content-body">
      <p class="intro-link"><em>Flooring is a major phase in any remodel. See how it fits into the construction sequence in our <a href="/home-renovation-guide">Ultimate Home Renovation Guide</a>.</em></p>

      <h2>Choosing the Right Floor Beneath Your Feet</h2>
      <p>Replacing your floors is one of the most visually impactful renovations you can undertake. The right flooring unifies a home, reflects light, and dictates the acoustic feel of a room. However, it is also an investment that you will walk on, spill on, and drop things on every single day. Therefore, choosing the right material is a delicate balance of aesthetics, budget, and durability.</p>
      <p>Use our interactive estimator above to understand the financial reality of different materials, and read the breakdown below to understand how each material performs in the real world.</p>

      <h3>1. Solid Hardwood: The Timeless Classic</h3>
      <p>Solid hardwood floors are exactly what they sound like: solid planks of wood (usually oak, maple, or hickory) milled from a single piece of timber. They are nailed or stapled down to a wooden subfloor.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Unmatched natural beauty, incredible longevity (can last 100+ years), can be sanded and refinished multiple times to remove scratches or change the stain color, and offers the highest Return on Investment (ROI) for resale value.</li>
        <li><strong>Cons:</strong> It is generally the most expensive option. Hardwood is highly susceptible to moisture; it expands and contracts with humidity and will warp if exposed to standing water. It cannot be installed in bathrooms or below-grade basements. It is also relatively soft and will scratch under the claws of large dogs or sharp high heels.</li>
        <li><strong>Best For:</strong> Living rooms, dining rooms, bedrooms, and hallways in high-end homes.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>2. Luxury Vinyl Plank (LVP): The Modern Workhorse</h3>
      <p>LVP has revolutionized the flooring industry in the last decade. It consists of a rigid core (often a stone-plastic composite), a printed photographic layer that mimics wood or stone, and a clear, durable "wear layer" on top. The planks click together to form a "floating floor."</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pros:</strong> High-quality LVP is 100% waterproof, making it suitable for any room in the house, including bathrooms, kitchens, and basements. It is highly resistant to scratches and dents, making it the premier choice for homes with pets and young children. It is also highly DIY-friendly, which can save thousands in labor costs.</li>
        <li><strong>Cons:</strong> While premium LVP looks incredibly realistic, it still lacks the authentic "feel" and acoustic thud of real solid wood. It cannot be refinished; if a plank is deeply gouged, it must be completely replaced. It does not add as much resale value to a luxury home as real hardwood.</li>
        <li><strong>Best For:</strong> Whole-house installations in active family homes, basements, kitchens, and rental properties.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>3. Laminate: The Budget-Friendly Alternative</h3>
      <p>Laminate flooring is similar to LVP in that it uses a photographic layer to mimic wood and clicks together as a floating floor. However, its core is made from high-density fiberboard (HDF), which is an engineered wood product.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Laminate is very affordable. The photographic technology has advanced to the point where premium laminate often looks more realistic than LVP. The top melamine wear layer is incredibly hard and highly resistant to scratches and fading from sunlight.</li>
        <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Because the core is made of wood byproducts, standard laminate is highly susceptible to water damage. If water seeps into the seams, the planks will swell, buckle, and are permanently ruined. (Note: "Water-resistant" laminates exist, but they are generally not 100% waterproof like LVP). It can also sound hollow or "clicky" when walked on if a high-quality underlayment is not used.</li>
        <li><strong>Best For:</strong> Living areas and bedrooms in budget-conscious renovations where water exposure is minimal.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>4. Porcelain and Ceramic Tile: The Indestructible Option</h3>
      <p>Tile is made from clay that is fired in a kiln at incredibly high temperatures. Porcelain is fired hotter and longer than standard ceramic, making it denser and more water-resistant.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Tile is essentially waterproof and incredibly durable. It will not scratch, dent, or fade. It is the only acceptable material for building a custom shower pan. It also pairs beautifully with radiant underfloor heating systems.</li>
        <li><strong>Cons:</strong> It is hard and cold underfoot (without radiant heat). Standing on tile for long periods (like cooking in a kitchen) can be tough on joints. It is also completely unforgiving; drop a glass on tile, and it will shatter. Installation is labor-intensive, messy, and expensive, requiring specialized tools like wet saws. The grout lines require periodic sealing and maintenance to prevent discoloration.</li>
        <li><strong>Best For:</strong> Bathrooms, entryways, mudrooms, and kitchens. Also popular for entire homes in hot, humid climates (like Florida or Arizona) because it stays cool.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>5. Carpet: Comfort and Acoustics</h3>
      <p>Wall-to-wall carpeting has fallen out of favor for main living areas in recent years, but it still holds a massive share of the flooring market.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pros:</strong> It is unmatched in terms of softness, warmth, and comfort underfoot. It is also the best material for acoustic control; it deadens sound, preventing echoes and muffling footsteps between floors. It is generally the cheapest material to buy and install.</li>
        <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Carpet traps dust, dander, and allergens, requiring constant vacuuming and professional steam cleaning. It stains easily and shows wear patterns in high-traffic areas over time. It has a relatively short lifespan compared to hard surfaces and generally lowers the resale value of a home if used outside of bedrooms.</li>
        <li><strong>Best For:</strong> Bedrooms, playrooms, and second-story floors where sound dampening is desired.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Hidden Costs of Flooring Installation</h3>
      <p>When budgeting, the cost of the material is only half the story. Always account for:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Demolition and Disposal:</strong> Tearing up old carpet is easy, but chipping out old ceramic tile is backbreaking work that contractors charge heavily for.</li>
        <li><strong>Subfloor Preparation:</strong> Hard surface floors require a perfectly flat subfloor. If your concrete slab is uneven or your wooden joists are sagging, the contractor will need to use self-leveling compound or replace plywood, which adds significant cost.</li>
        <li><strong>Trim and Transitions:</strong> Installing new floors almost always requires replacing the baseboards (or installing quarter-round shoe molding) and adding transition strips where the new floor meets different materials in doorways.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>By using the calculator to estimate costs and understanding the unique properties of each material, you can confidently select a floor that fits your lifestyle and your budget.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    const floorData = [
      {
        id: 'hardwood',
        name: 'Solid Hardwood',
        pricePerSqFt: 10.50, // Mid-range material + labor
        durability: 'High (Can be refinished)',
        maintenance: 'Medium (Avoid water, use special cleaners)',
        waterproof: 'No',
        color: '#8B4513'
      },
      {
        id: 'lvp',
        name: 'Luxury Vinyl Plank (LVP)',
        pricePerSqFt: 6.50,
        durability: 'Very High (Scratch & dent resistant)',
        maintenance: 'Low (Sweep and damp mop)',
        waterproof: 'Yes (100%)',
        color: '#4682B4'
      },
      {
        id: 'laminate',
        name: 'Laminate',
        pricePerSqFt: 5.50,
        durability: 'High (Resists scratching/fading well)',
        maintenance: 'Medium (Must avoid standing water)',
        waterproof: 'No (Water-resistant at best)',
        color: '#D2B48C'
      },
      {
        id: 'tile',
        name: 'Porcelain Tile',
        pricePerSqFt: 12.00, // High labor cost
        durability: 'Extreme (Will outlast the house)',
        maintenance: 'Medium (Grout requires cleaning/sealing)',
        waterproof: 'Yes (100%)',
        color: '#708090'
      },
      {
        id: 'carpet',
        name: 'Carpet (Nylon/Polyester)',
        pricePerSqFt: 4.50,
        durability: 'Low to Medium (Shows wear patterns)',
        maintenance: 'High (Vacuuming and steam cleaning)',
        waterproof: 'No',
        color: '#9370DB'
      }
    ];

    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const sqftInput = document.getElementById('sqft-input');
      const resultsContainer = document.getElementById('flooring-results');

      const formatCurrency = (num) => '$' + Math.round(num).toLocaleString();

      function renderCards() {
        const sqft = parseFloat(sqftInput.value) || 0;
        resultsContainer.innerHTML = '';

        // Add 10% waste factor
        const totalSqFt = Math.ceil(sqft * 1.1);

        floorData.forEach(floor => {
          const totalCost = totalSqFt * floor.pricePerSqFt;

          const card = document.createElement('div');
          card.className = 'floor-card';
          card.style.borderTop = `4px solid ${floor.color}`;

          card.innerHTML = `
            <h3 class="floor-title">${floor.name}</h3>
            <div class="cost-breakdown">
              <div class="cost-total">${formatCurrency(totalCost)}</div>
              <div class="cost-per">Est. ${formatCurrency(floor.pricePerSqFt)} / sq ft (Installed)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="floor-stats">
              <div class="stat-row"><strong>Materials Needed:</strong> <span>${totalSqFt} sq ft (inc. 10% waste)</span></div>
              <div class="stat-row"><strong>Waterproof:</strong> <span style="color:${floor.waterproof.includes('Yes') ? '#38a169' : '#e53e3e'}">${floor.waterproof}</span></div>
              <div class="stat-row"><strong>Durability:</strong> <span>${floor.durability}</span></div>
              <div class="stat-row"><strong>Maintenance:</strong> <span>${floor.maintenance}</span></div>
            </div>
          `;
          resultsContainer.appendChild(card);
        });
      }

      sqftInput.addEventListener('input', renderCards);

      // Initial render
      renderCards();
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.6; }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }

    .flooring-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin-top: 2rem; text-align: left; }

    .floor-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--bg-color) 60%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 1.5rem; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); transition: transform 0.2s; }
    .floor-card:hover { transform: translateY(-3px); border-color: var(--text-secondary); }

    .floor-title { margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-primary); }

    .cost-breakdown { text-align: center; padding: 1rem 0; margin-bottom: 1rem; background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--bg-color) 40%, #000); border-radius: 6px; }
    .cost-total { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: bold; color: var(--accent-color); line-height: 1.1; }
    .cost-per { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-top: 0.2rem; }

    .floor-stats { font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; }
    .stat-row { display: flex; flex-direction: column; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; padding-bottom: 0.8rem; border-bottom: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--border-color) 50%, transparent); }
    .stat-row:last-child { border-bottom: none; margin-bottom: 0; padding-bottom: 0; }
    .stat-row strong { color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.2rem; }
    .stat-row span { color: var(--text-primary); font-weight: 500; }

    .content-body h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .content-body h3 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .content-body p { margin-bottom: 1.2rem; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .content-body ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; }
    .content-body li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .content-body a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline; }
    .intro-link { text-align: center; font-size: 1.1rem; padding: 1rem; background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--card-bg) 50%, transparent); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
